The genus 

Lychnophora
(Asteraceae)

includes 35 species, of which 23 are found in different phytophysiognomies in the Brazilian Cerrado. This genus demonstrates wide interspecies morphological variation, including sizes of treelet, shrub, and (rarely) subshrub and presence of slightly branched stem branches, alternate sessile leathery and sheathless leaves, terminal inflorescences, and cypselae with inconspicuous carpopodia (

; 

; 

, 

). 

Lychnophora

is a chemically complex genus with great structural diversity of specialized metabolites, such as sesquiterpene hydrocarbons, oxygenated sesquiterpenes, flavonoids, and sesquiterpene lactones (

).


Lychnophora pinaster
Mart.

, known as “arnica” and “arnica mineira,” is an endemic species at risk of extinction located in the 

campo 
rupestre

of the Brazilian Cerrado of 
Minas Gerais
. The aerial parts are used in traditional medicine in alcoholic preparations to treat inflammation, contusions, sprains, bruises, insect bites, and other injuries (

; 

). Previous studies have demonstrated the presence of compounds in 

L. pinaster

with trypanocidal (caffeic acid, isochlorogenic acid, vitexin, isovitexin), antibacterial and anti-inflammatory (α- amyrin, quercetin, lupeol, stigmasterol, sitosterol), analgesic and antipyretic (friedelin) actions, corroborating popular use (

; 

; 

).

Altitude variations control multiple abiotic factors such as rainfall patterns, extreme temperatures, cloud cover, atmospheric pressure, soil quality, and vegetation cover (

). These, in turn, change the morphology, physiology, and genetic patterns of plant species (

; 

; 

; 

), leading to local adaptation of isolated populations (

; 

). As a consequence of isolation, different phenotypes are generated among populations (

). Altitudinal variations also alter population genetics, triggering the inbreeding process and leading to strong population structure and local adaptation of species (

; 

; 

), a decline in gene flow, and high intrapopulation variability (

; and 

).

Angelica archangelica
L. populations collected at three high altitudes in India (3500, 3200, and 2200 m ) produced limonene, γ- terpinene, terpinolene, and bornyl acetate (
). Essential oils of H. italicum
ssp. microphyllum
populations collected in the mountain ( 600–1250 m ) and coastal ( 0–60 m ) regions of Italy contained different chemical compositions: individuals from mountainous regions had significant geraniol, α- cis/trans -bergamotene, and α- guaiene concentrations, while those from coastal regions had significant nerolidol, cis -β- guaiol and trans -caryophyllene concentrations (
).

In Brazil , the Cerrado biome is marked by extreme abiotic factors (
;
), especially in the state of Minas Gerais . The evolution of the Cerrado biome in Minas Gerais contributed to the appearance of many endemic species (
) so that it is possible to find a large number of endemic species associated with mountainous complexes (
;
).
Lychnophora pinaster
is found in the
campo rupestre
located in the mountain ranges (
) with wide variation in altitude (
800–2000 m
), soil, and climate conditions. The altitudinal variation of the mountain ranges of Minas Gerais can function as a geographical barrier for
L. pinaster
populations, reflected in the diversity and genetic structure of the population and consequent intra- and interpopulation genetic divergences. In addition, the action of climatic factors caused by altitude variations can promote variations in the chemical composition of essential oils as a response mechanism to the xeromorphic and seasonal environment of the
campo rupestre
, increasing the chemical diversity of the species. However, little is known about the effects of altitudinal variations on the chemical composition of essential oils and the genetic composition of
L. pinaster
. The aim of the present study was to investigate the impact of altitude variations on the genetic

The predominant chemical constituent of essential oils of the MrBH02 population was identified as norsesquiterpene 4-oxo-15-noreudesman-11-ene based on 1 D ( 1 H and 13 C NMR; DEPT) and 2D (HSQC and HMBC) NMR data. The correlations observed in the HMBC experiment between the hydrogens at δ 2.47 and 2.37 (H-6) with carbons at δ 214.81 (J-3), 152.91 (J-3), 44.35 (J-2), and 33.84 (J-3) are compatible with 15-nor-eudesman and also justify the carbonyl positioned in C-4. Furthermore, the 15-nor-eudesman-type sesquiterpenoids have been isolated from Asteraceae species (
); they are characterized by NMR here for the first time from genus
Lychnophora .

2010; 

) and essential oils of 

L. ericoides
Mart. (
Lyra et al., 2008
)

. The chemical composition of essential oils of 

L. pinaster

suggests genetic differences between populations and the influence of climatic conditions and altitude variations in the different regions where

The MrBH altitude varied between 1200 and 
2000 m
(

; Barros and Magalh˜aes Jr., 2018). The altitudinal gradient changed the chemical composition and genetic diversity of species (

) by the action of different environmental patterns, which lead to different genetic selection between populations of a species (

) and, therefore, local adaptation (García-Fern´andez et al., 2012).

Analysis of Molecular Variance (AMOVA) results showed that 

L. pinaster

has inter-population genetic diversity (Table S4). The Hardy–Weinberg equilibrium (HWE) analysis performed on each allele per population indicated that most alleles are in equilibrium, confirmed by similar values between Ho and He (Table 02). Allele frequencies are expected to be in HWE, indicating that populations maintain their genetic diversity (

). Therefore, 

L. pinaster

populations demonstrated maintenance of their genetic diversity in this study. Furthermore, results showed that all 

L. pinaster

populations have low nucleotide diversity, which implies genetic variation of genetic polymorphisms between populations. These populations undergo fragmentation processes due to the effect of geographical barriers, which has been reported previously for other species (

; 

; 

).

Geographical isolation increases interpopulation diversity, and nucleotide diversity, heterozygosity, and the within-population inbreeding coefficient (FIS) describe population isolation behavior (

; 

). The populations North 01 and 02 and MrBH 02 presented negative inbreeding (FIS) values, indicating that each population is in HWE (

). Although North 03 and MrBH 01 presented positive values of FIS (0.014 ± 0.02 and 0.007 ± 0.02, respectively), indicating the possibility of inbreeding (

), inbreeding was not occurring because a majority of alleles followed HWE (results of chi-squared tests; 
Table 2
). Furthermore, 

L. pinaster

populations had high allele frequencies (P) values and low nucleotide diversity values (
Table 2
), indicating a higher presence of homozygotes in 

L. pinaster

populations. Native populations have a high frequency of homozygotes caused by changes in the landscape, habitat degradation, and other factors that partially impair gene flow (

).

The first Mantel test, involving all sampled populations, revealed a positive correlation between genetic diversity and altitude (R =0.386; 
p
= 0.047). The second Mantel test utilized only the altitude and FST values of North (
700–900 m
) and MrBH (
>
1350 m
) populations and revealed a strong positive correlation between genetic diversity and altitude (R = 0.942; 
p
= 0.027). In addition to Mantel tests, MrBH populations presented many private alleles (
Table 2
), showing a unique genetic contribution in a population, with implications for species conservation (

).

Populations found at high altitudes (above 
1350 m
) are genetically different from populations found at altitudes below 
1300 m
. The analysis of population structure (
Fig. 6
) shows that MrBH 01 (
1498 m
) and MRBH 02 (
1366 m
) populations were genetically distinct from North populations (
Tables 2
and 
3
), contributing to the genetic divergence of 

L. pinaster

. Altitude is one of the geographical factors with the greatest impact on the diversity of native populations, culminating in the appearance of different genetic population patterns (

; 

; 

). Populations found at high altitudes show high genetic diversity (

), increasing their ability to adapt to the biotic and abiotic factors (

), leading to the emergence of local adaptations (García-Fernandez´et al., 2012). The high genetic diversity and structure of MrBH 

L. pinaster

are caused by high altitudes, selecting distinct genetic pools. Altitude variations have been demonstrated to provide a strong population structure leading to distinct genetic pools in species (García-Fern´andez et al., 2012; 

).

The confirmation of taxonomic identification of the species was conducted by specialists in the genus PhD. Jo˜ao Semir from the Institute of Biology, State University of Campinas, and PhD. Marcelo Monge (Federal University of Uberlˆandia). The identifications were based on specialist knowledge, comparisons with other materials, and published literature (

; 

; 

). Exsiccates were deposited at the UEC herbarium of the State University of Campinas (UEC 179320, 179321, 179322, 208036, 208026, 208030, 208028, and 208038). Plant material was collected by authorization of the Ministry of the Environment of 
Brazil
(ICMBio: 22772–6; Sis- Gen/MMA: A01F803) and the Forestry Institute of the state of 
Minas Gerais
(authorizations 005/2017 and 006/2017).

Qualitative analysis of the chemical composition of essential oils was conducted using a QP-5000 GC-MS (Shimadzu Corporation, Kyoto , Japan ). A DB-5 capillary column ( 30 m × 0.25 mm × 0.25 μm) was used in GC experiments, and helium was used as carrier gas at a constant flow of 1.0 mL min 1 . The injector was kept at 220 ◦ C, injecting 1 μL of solution ( 1 mg essential oil/1 mL ethyl acetate, chromatographic grade) and a split ratio of 1:20. The GC oven temperature was programmed from 60 ◦ C to 240 ◦ C at 3 ◦ C min 1 . Electron ionization (EI) was used at 70 eV, and mass spectra were collected over the range of m/z 40–450. The transfer line was maintained at 240 ◦ C. Identification of chemical constituents was carried out by comparing mass spectra of substances with those in the database (Nist 62.lib) and linear retention indexes found in the literature (
). Linear retention indexes were obtained from the injection of a mixture of n -alkanes (C 9 –C 24 ), using an equation described by
.

Demultiplex procedures, construction of RAD loci , discovery, and annotation of SNP markers were conducted via pipeline in STACKS v.2.45 (
;
;
). Reads of
L. pinaster
samples were first demultiplexed using the radtags software and individualized into different files in the. fastq format based on each sample’ s barcodes (6–8bp). Several filters were applied in this first stage to select high-quality sample reads : the quality score filter (-q), the filter for eliminating readings with the non-call based function (-c), and the function that prevents the selection of barcodes with more than one mismatch (-r). After this procedure, sequences with a length of 90 bp were selected, and low quality sequences were discarded. The second genotyping stage consisted of constructing an SNP catalog using the ustacks software. In this software, the method for SNP selection was applied because the species does not have a reference genome, followed by the following parameters: maximum allowed distance between stacks (M = 2); maximum allowed distance for secondary alignments (N = 4, M +2); and minimum coverage with three sequences for each RAD locus (m =3). The third step consisted of constructing a common SNP catalog using the cstacks software. During this process, a difference greater than two (2) between the same locus was not allowed to prevent loci from overlapping. In addition, each SNP marker was required to be present in at least 60% of total samples (-r = 0.5), with a minimum frequency restricted to 5% and observed heterozygosity (Ho) limited to a maximum of 75%.

Procedures for describing 

L. pinaster

diversity and population structure were performed via STACKS v.2.45, using the 
ctacks
software (

; 

; 

). Allele frequency, nucleotide diversity (π), number of alleles (A), private alleles (
Ap
), observed heterozygosity (
Ho
), expected heterozygosity (
He
), observed homozygosity, expected homozygosity, and the pairwise inbreeding coefficient (FST) were estimated using the 
cstacks
software. Tests for deviation from the Hardy–Weinberg equilibrium (HWE) for proportions in each population were performed using the 
pegas
package (

). The hierarchical analysis of molecular variance (AMOVA) was performed with eight populations considering 19999 permutations. Individuals were grouped by the ADMIXTURE v1.2 software, and the best value of inferred populations (
K
) was implemented by the cross-validation method (

). 
K
values describe genetic clusters of 

L. pinaster

populations.

The Bayesian approach using the BayeScan software v. 2.1 (

; 

) and the PCAdapt model (

; 

) was chosen to identify the presence of SNPs under positive selection. The Bayesian approach can identify the allelic frequency of different populations and indicate which loci are under neutral selection and which are under positive selection according to the geographical distance between populations (

; 

). The model is a logistic regression based on the overall pairwise fixation coefficient (FST) values, capable of dividing the

genotypic effects of neutral loci and loci under positive selection, establishing frequency values for each marker. The second approach to detect SNP markers under positive selection was the PCAdapt method implemented by the 
pcadapt
package using 
R
software (

). This model also uses FST values indicated by SNP markers that make up the population structure and a series of mathematical probabilities. Furthermore, the model indicates which markers are neutral and which are under positive selection (

; 

). The PCAdapt model expresses PCA, showing how SNP markers can promote the selection process in populations under study.

